events.name: Post I/O Meetup Summer 2014 - Google technologies

venue.name: Bosque Brewing Co
venue.address_1: 8900 San Mateo Blvd. NE, Ste. I

events.description:
Hopefully everyone is back from vacation and ready to go over all the new Google technologies with us.  This will be a jam packed meetup.

We'll cover one of the hottest technologies to come out of Google I/O end of June - #AndroidWear .  We'll have on hand both the LG #GWatch and the Samsung #GearLive to try out yourselves.  In addition, I will bring a sample demo app of an Android Wear watchface so you may jump right in to creating wear apps.

#Polymer !  Who is excited about Polymer?  We are.  We'll go over this new library set of web components and how moving forward this will change how the web is developed.

Design!  Calling all designers.  The new Android L focuses a ton on design characteristics.  We'll cover what this means for current Android developers, designers and go over the key differences from KitKat.

Android Studio is now Beta!  Still using Eclipse?  No problem.  We will go over the differences and how both environments can co-exist if you want them to as well as what sets Android Studio apart.

#Cardboard!  You may have seen or heard about this nifty Google contraption.  It's like Occulus VR only - different.  Come see a demo of Virtual Reality glasses in the form of your smartphone and well, cardboard.

Did we miss something you want to talk about?  No problemo.  As always, everyone is welcome and we will happily discuss any other Google technology you'd like to.

Hope to see you all there!

PS: We have _some_ swag to giveaway. ;)

events.name: Android Wear Workshop part 1

venue.name: Bosque Brewing Co
venue.address_1: 8900 San Mateo Blvd. NE, Ste. I

events.description:
https://plus.google.com/events/cjvrfsdafkgaq9davn5n5jqn724

Summer is just about over and fall is about to start (as well as the NFL season) :)

Android Wear watches are an entirely new ecosystem for Android and we're going to be doing 2 upcoming workshops on how to write code for them in Android Studio.

Several of our members have already created apps for Android Wear.  Come get started on making one yourself.

We'll go over project setup, and making your own watchface using a few open-source projects that provide a great start.

A watchface can be super simple, or more complex depending on what you want to do with it.

Let us help!  You'll learn the ins and outs of getting started with Android Wear.

We will have on hand several Android-Wear watches to play with.  You won't need your own watch to get started and may use the emulator completely if you'd like.

Please bring your laptops and have the latest version of Android Studio installed as well as the Android 4.4W SDK.
http://developer.android.com/sdk/installing/studio.html

Once installed, open the Android SDK Manager (located in sdk/tools) and download the 4.4W SDK.  We'll help you setup the emulator/s for round and square if you need any help. 

As always, we're happy to discuss any other Google technologies you are working with and everyone is welcome!

Hope to see you all there!

events.name: Exploring Material Design

venue.name: Bosque Brewing Co
venue.address_1: 8900 San Mateo Blvd. NE, Ste. I

events.description:
Some of the goals of Google's new Material Design language is to create a visual language that synthesizes classic principles of good design with the innovation and possibility of technology and science. Grounded in tactile reality and inspired by paper and ink, this design language helps the fluidity of transition through space and a system of motion. Join us as we go through the basics, best practices, and evaluate some examples.

One of our members Chris will be on hand explaining and demonstrating how he converted one of his apps over to Material Design.

If you'd like to get a jump start, please read the newly updated Material Design documentation.
http://www.google.com/design/spec/whats-new/whats-new.html
http://www.google.com/design/spec/material-design/introduction.html

Hope to see you all there!

events.name: Marshmallow runtime permissions.

venue.name: Bosque Brewing Co
venue.address_1: 8900 San Mateo Blvd. NE, Ste. I

events.description:
To protect the system's integrity and the user's privacy, Android runs each app in a limited access sandbox. If the app wants to use resources or information outside of its sandbox, the app has to explicitly request permission.

Android 6.0 Marshmallow saw the introduction of runtime permissions. These permissions are granted (or rejected) by the user at runtime rather than at installtime.

Depending on the type of permission the app requests, the system may grant the permission automatically, or the system may ask the user to grant the permission.

We'll be talking about this and any other topics you'd like.

As always, everyone is welcome.

Please bring your laptops if you'd like to work on some code.

venue.name: Bosque Brewing Co
venue.address_1: 8900 San Mateo Blvd. NE, Ste. I

events.description:
Happy New Year everyone!

We'll be kicking off 2019 with discussions of new phone formats and how to prepare, as well as the incoming 5G and what it will mean for new apps and what may be done.

Working on anything new? Show it off!

Need some help with an API? We have members who are experts on most of the ones you might encounter in Android like Maps.

Need some help with some code? Be it Android or another Google technology, let us give it a shot.

It's open topics, so anything goes!

As always everyone is welcome, and we encourage you to bring a friend.

Bring your laptops if you need some help with code or just want to show something off.

Hope to see you all soon.

Best,
Dustin

events.name: Google IO aftermath and Firebase...

venue.name: Restoration Pizza
venue.address_1: 5161 Lang Ave NE Suite A

events.description:
It's been a minute. Let's regroup and talk about Google IO last month. Plenty of time to digest what was talked about, what was seen, scary AI...

Firebase? Are you using firebase yet? If you are using Google Analytics still, you need to switch by Oct of 2019 (my friend called this yrs ago). I recently switched my current apps over to Firebase and implemented deep links, analytics, crashlytics (formerly owned by Twitter), and ads. So I got you if you need any help.

Anyone with a Pixel 3 or 3a? I want to hold one, use one, please bring it if you got it! I'm not sure I buy the hype so far.

Are you concerned with the over 512 MB of built in AI in the new Android? Let's discuss. Yes .5 gig. Half a gig in memory is a concern of mine since most flagships are between 4-8 gigs of RAM, so it's a huge chunk.

Do you have another Google topic you'd like to discuss? Great!

I'm looking for a co-organizer to help with running GDG Albuquerque. Programmers wanted, though not required. Please let me know if you are interested by attending, and also send me a note on here.

Hope to see you all there. As always, everyone is welcome and please bring a friend.

Bring a laptop if you need any help with code.

See you soon.
